Introduction

 

This Family History is based mainly on the results obtained by utilizing on-line resources at Ancestry.com, the records of Monroe County, Ohio and personal information. Also, several cousins have provided key information. During the time of the collection of the <<<<<<< HEAD basic information for my parents family history, I discovered that I could extract enough information to begin to construct a more detailed history of my Grandparents, Clifford and Mattie Hall Moose. Apparently, no one has published a History or Family Tree on Martha Ellen (Mattie) Halls Family since my initial searching found no connection to any on-line family trees or other sources. However, after establishing several family connections, I was able to find several family trees on-line that contained considerable information on some branches of Mattie Halls Family. I also discovered new cousins who provided valuable leads and and family information. ======= basic information for my parent s family history, I discovered that I could extract enough information to begin to construct a more detailed history of my Grandparents, Clifford and Mattie Hall Moose. Apparently, no one has published a History or Family Tree on Martha Ellen (Mattie) Hall s Family since my initial searching found no connection to any on-line family trees or other sources. However, after establishing several family connections, I was able to find several family trees on-line that contained considerable information on some branches of Mattie Hall s Family. I also discovered new cousins who provided valuable leads and and family information. >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Research in Monroe County is difficult because of the fire that burned vital records in 1867. However, the excellent work by the Monroe County Genealogical Society with the books and CDs that they offer has certainly been of prime inportance to me in writing this history. This history was written initially for my own family.

 

My mother was Helen Mayme Moose, the 7th child of Clifford and Martha Moose. She married Carl Willard Weber of Summit Township in Monroe County in 1934. My older brother Jack <<<<<<< HEAD and I were born in Jacob Webers house near Lewisville. Around Thanksgiving Day in 1936, my father was accidentally shot in the right wrist in a hunting accident and as a result he had a difficult time obtaining meaningful employment. This was a significant event for our family as there were no hire the handicap laws at ======= and I were born in Jacob Weber s house near Lewisville. Around Thanksgiving Day in 1936, my father was accidentally shot in the right wrist in a hunting accident and as a result he had a difficult time obtaining meaningful employment. This was a significant event for our family as there were no hire the handicap laws at >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 that time. So we moved around a lot in the oilfields as my Father tried to find descent jobs.

 

In 1938 or 1939, we moved to Gladwin, Michigan where my father had obtained a job in the oilfields most likely through the <<<<<<< HEAD help of his brother-in-law, Will Lafferee. After Will and Dads sister Lilly moved away to Deerfield, Michigan in 1940, our family grew up somewhat isolated from all other family members with the exceptions of two cousins and my uncle and aunt. I seldom saw either of the two grandparents who were alive when I was born. As a result I knew very little about my ancestors, aunts, uncles and cousins. So this is one of the reasons for this endeavor as I tried to find out all I could about my parents ======= help of his brother-in-law, Will Lafferee. After Will and Dad s sister Lilly moved away to Deerfield, Michigan in 1940, our family grew up somewhat isolated from all other family members with the exceptions of two cousins and my uncle and aunt. I seldom saw either of the two grandparents who were alive when I was born. As a result I knew very little about my ancestors, aunts, uncles and cousins. The basis for a portion of <<<<<<< HEAD this history was found in the Family Trees on Ancestry.coms, One World Tree. ======= this history was found in the Family Trees on Ancestry.com s, One World Tree. >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 When possible, this information has been verified by other sources such as census listings and Family Collection Data, County Records, Death Records, reading grave markers and through books obtained from the Monroe <<<<<<< HEAD County Branch of the Ohio Genealogical Society. However, not all of the information included in this book has been fully substantiated. On Ancestry.com, I found Family Trees1,2,3 that traced the history of the Moose Family. Also found was information on the Moose Family in Monroe County Ohio Families published by the Monroe County ======= County Branch of the Ohio Genealogical Society. However, not all of the information included in this book has been fully substantiated. On Ancestry.com, I found Family Trees1,2,3 that traced the history of the Moose Family. Also found was information on the Moose Family in Monroe County Ohio Families published by the Monroe County >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Genealogical Society4. An article on the Moose Family submitted by Dick Moose5 provided starter information and Dick also provided other documents on the Moose Family of Monroe County.

 

Some of the additional names associated with the Moose Family are Moore, Baker, Nalley, Shafer, Hess, Vanwy, Armbuster, Hoffman, Earley, Fuger, Rouse, Bates, Piatt, Weber, Doan, Orange Mobberly, Roach, Winland and Repple.

 

Key names in the Hall Family are Hall, Hamilton, Ullom, Mitchell, Wood, Bowen, Bashore, Wenrich, Mauer, Moon, Humphrey, Wilsford, Burgess, Dilworth, Hill, Wood, Osborne and Teague. No on-line family tree could be found for the Hall Family.

 

In this History, I will attempt a detailed study of the ancestors and descendants of the Clifford Moose and Mattie Hall Families in Monroe County and beyond. I will also include as many photographs as I can obtain.

 

I would like to give special thanks to Marlene and Dick Moose, Marge Billman, Chris Creamer, Shelby and John Perry, Carrie Bates, Ralph Christman and Linda Grible for their valuable contributions in helping me track the Moose Family and for providing several photographs. In particular, Connie Koniski, who provided information, guidance and photos and a GEDCOM file of her work on the Moose Family has been very helpful in <<<<<<< HEAD forming this family history. .

Chapter One The Moose Family of Chapter One The Moose Family of >>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 w:st="on">Monroe County, Ohio

 

Family Trees on Ancestry.com (One World Tree)1,2,3, indicated that the Moose Family came from Germany to Pennsylvania. The original German name was most likely Mussgenug or Mussgnug with other modifications in spelling. On Ancestry.com, their opinion is that the Moose name was derived from Moos and this could be true in some instances. But nearly every Family Tree covering the Moose Family of Pennsylvania, Ohio and North Carolina, states that it is derived from Mussgenug or Mussgnug. Some of these names were found in the Lehigh County, Pennsylvania Records and various family trees. Records of the Union Church in Lehigh County reveal the births of William and Daniel Mussgenug as the sons of Jacob and Elizabeth Hoffman6 Mussgenug. An un-named on-line Moose ======= normal'>Elizabeth Hoffman6 Mussgenug. An un-named on-line Moose >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Family Tree7 source states that John Jacob Mussgnug and wife Elizabeth Hoffman had nine children, 7 boys and 2 girls. As mentioned on the Lehigh County Genealogical Site the births of William in 1777 and Daniel in 1783 are listed but none of those born in between, such as John Sr. born in 17786. Also there is a footnote in these records stating that Jacob Mussgenung of Whitehall Township married Elizabeth Hoffman, daughter of the late Martin Hoffman on 25 Feb 1766.

 

In the Records of the Egypt Reformed Church in Lehigh County there is the birth of Jacob Mussgenug on 29 Jan 1786. His parents were David and Anna Maria.

 

Beginning with John Moose Sr.9, 10

 

Investigation of John Moose Sr. and his children begins with comments by Monroe County Genealogist, Catherine F. Fedorchak, who wrote about John Moose Sr.9 in 1970. She stated that John Moose Sr. was in the war of 1812 and his grave marker is in one of the three Moose Ridge Cemeteries. John was stationed at Ft. Meigs* in Maumee, Ohio and after 3 or 4 months he was granted a leave for 20 to 30 days as he was not sure how much time would be required. While on leave he became ill and was shown in several muster sheets as AWOL. However, this was later resolved by written deposition by Thomas Floid (Floyd). This deposition was <<<<<<< HEAD submitted along with a hand written leave of absence to the Auditors office in 1824 or 1825 so that John Sr. could collect back wages. Johns enlistment began on 13 Sept.1813 and ran for 6 months. He was a private under the command of Capt. John Howell in Col. John Delongs regiment10.

======= submitted along with a hand written leave of absence to the Auditor s office in 1824 or 1825 so that John Sr. could collect back wages. John s enlistment began on 13 Sept.1813 and ran for 6 months. He was a private under the command of Capt. John Howell in Col. John Delong s regiment10.

>>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711

 

The Woods-Bettridge Family Tree1 on Ancestry.com states that John Sr. was married twice. His first wife, Mary Ann, was the mother of Jacob, Joseph, Elizabeth, Mary Ann, John Jr., Sabina, Sarah and probably George. His second wife Rachel was the mother of Henry ======= style='mso-spacerun:yes'> His second wife Rachel was the mother of Henry >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 H., Martha and Emily. Mary Ann is reported to have died in 1836. John died on 10 Aug 1841 and his wife Rachel died on 14 Feb 1846. A bill granting land to the soldiers of the War of 1812 was passed on 28 Sept 1850 after John Sr. had died. At this time John Moose Jr. had himself appointed as guardian of the minor children of John Sr. and Rachel in order to apply for benefits which were <<<<<<< HEAD due them9. The minor children ======= due them9. The minor children >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 were Henry, Martha and Emily2. These are supposedly the children of John and Rachel per Woods-Bettridge. John Moose Sr. was born in Lehigh County, Pa. on 16 Sep 1778 and died in Monroe County on 18 Mar 1842**.

 

*Fort Meigs, just outside of Maumee, Ohio and on the Maumee River, was named after the Govenor of Ohio and was a hub of the War of 1812 in the west. During the War of 1812, it was a prime target of a few British Regulars and the Ohio born Shawnee Leader, Tecumseh, and about 1000 Indians. Ft. Meigs was commanded by William Henry Harrison the future president of the United States. Towards the end of the war, W.H. Harrison and his troops chased the British and Indians into Canada and this is where Tecumseh was killed.

 

**As already mentioned, there still remains a degree of uncertainty as to whether John Moose Sr. is a direct <<<<<<< HEAD ancestor of Clifford Moose or possibly a granduncle. Dick Mooses opinion was also published in a book, Monroe County, Ohio Families4. All ======= ancestor of Clifford Moose or possibly a granduncle. Dick Moose s opinion was also published in a book, Monroe County, Ohio Families 4. All >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 on-line family trees state that George Moose was an older son of John Moose Senior. In the only census in which George Moose designated the birth place of his parents, the 1880 Federal Census, he stated that they were born in Virginia. John and Mary Ann Moose were believed to have been born in PA. This adds a further degree of uncertainty but George and his wife were in their seventies at that time and one can not be sure which one of them provided this birthplace information.

 

The first to immigrate to America was said to be Johan Jacob Mussnug (Mussgenug)1,2,3 in 1752 settling in eastern Pa. Later the name was apparently changed to Moose and portions of the family moved west to Ohio; south to North Carolina while some remained in Pennsylvania. John Sr. is the father of John Moose Jr. who lived on Moose Ridge Road in Monroe County. As already mentioned he is said to be the father of George Moose, Clifford Mooses Grandfather1,2,3,10. Attachments cover the Moose (Mussgenug) Family and the Life of John Moose Jr. Other names in the Moose line are Hess, Fuger and Hoffman. The maiden names of Mary Ann and Rachel, John Sr.s wives, are not known. As already mentioned he is said to be the father of George Moose, Clifford Moose s Grandfather1,2,3,10. Attachments cover the Moose (Mussgenug) Family and the Life of John Moose Jr. Other names in the Moose line are Hess, Fuger and Hoffman. The maiden names of Mary Ann and Rachel, John Sr. s wives, are not known.

 

John Moose Sr. is considered by many to be the ======= style='mso-spacerun:yes'> John Moose Sr. is considered by many to be the >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 ancestor of the Moose Families who settled in Wayne Township, Monroe County and the Great-grandfather of Clifford Moose, however to the best of my knowledge, there is only strong circumstantial evidence concerning this relationship and no concrete proof has been found. I will present the all evidence for this conclusion in the following pages.

 

I have also been unable to find any records that make the clear connection between John Moose Sr. and <<<<<<< HEAD Jacob Mussgenug. Several unknown sources on Ancestry.coms, One World Tree, believe this relationship as well as the Herche, Harkey, Herge and Harcha Trees3 and Woods Bettridge1, all on Ancestry.com. John Moose Jrs.Death Cert and his brother Jacobs Death Cert list John Moose Sr. and Mary Ann as their parents. Unfortunately Georges parents are not listed on his Death ======= Jacob Mussgenug. Several unknown sources on Ancestry.com s, One World Tree, believe this relationship as well as the Herche, Harkey, Herge and Harcha Trees3 and Woods Bettridge1, all on Ancestry.com. John Moose Jr s.Death Cert and his brother Jacob s Death Cert list John Moose Sr. and Mary Ann as their parents. Unfortunately George s parents are not listed on his Death >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Certification.

In the 1820 Census of Wayne Township, Belmont County, John Moose is between the age of 25 and 45 and has one son 10-15 (Jacob, John Jr.), one son 16-18 (John Jr.or George), and one son 18-25 (Joseph). He has 3 daughters under 10, (Mary Ann, Sarah and Sabina), one female 18 to 26 (Elizabeth) and one female 25-45 (wife). This is apparently John Moose Sr. and one son is missing (George, 10-15 or 16-18?). There should be two sons 10-15. The three females under 10 are also not accounted for in the family tree on ancestry.com. One tree states that there were two daughters, Sabina and Sarah, and a son, Lewis but this is also not consistent with the 1820 census information. . From death certs we know that John Jr. and Jacob list their parents as John and Mary Ann. This could be considered evidence that George is not the son of John Moose Sr.

For this history, I will assume that Geroge is the son of John Moose Sr., since he certainly is of the correct age to be a son of John Sr. He also appears in Belmont County in the same area as John Sr., and moved to the same area of Monroe county around the same time as the known sons of John Sr. Finally, I could not trace any other family that George could have been a member of that were located in the Belmont County of Monroe County areas.

In 1880, neither an Ithamer or Homer is with Arsula and Issac nor can they be found in Monroe County. Also, it s almost certain that Arsula Moore is actually Arsula Moose. A copy of Homer Baker s Death Certificate states that he is the son of Isaac T. Baker and Sullie Moose*.

>>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711

2. John Moose Jr. ( John Sr.) (1806-1879)1,2,3,83

 

John Jr. was born in Greene County, PA on 30 May 1806, calculated from death record12, and was living in Wayne Township in the 1870 Federal Census. He and his wife, Emily, had real estate valued at $22,000 and personal estate valued at $ 360014. With the family was Henry H. Moose born in 1852; three farm laborers and a domestic servant.

This appears to be the Stephen Cecil Family and Stephen is no longer with the family, probably dying between 1860-1870. Connie Koniski174 told me that Stephen died in the Civil War. The death of a Stephen Cecil, Co H 36 Regiment OVI is reported. He died at the age of 33y 5m 20d, on 20 May 1865 in Baltimore, MD in Jarvis U.S.C.Hospital Ward C of Jaundice and Inflammation of the Brain132,133. His wife and 4 little children survive. The age does not match the census information but the references are thought to be reliable. Another reference has a military gravesite in Baltimore, MD for Stephen Cecil who died on 23 Jul 1865 (Louden Park National Cemetery Civil War Records on Ancestry.com).

 

Forrest A Cecil was born on 5 Jul 1875 in Monroe County. His mother is listed as Elizabeth Moose and his father is not listed. (1900 Census).

3. Joseph Meads, (John Sr., Mary Ann), born about 1843 entered Company F. of the 51st Illinois Infantry on 18 Jul 1862. On 19 Sep 1863 he was killed at Chickamauga146,146A,147.

 

According to correspondence between Lisa Meads Jump and Connie Koniski (24 Apr 2005)174 the following summarizes some of the family actions after 1860.

 

In 1860 Elisha, Mary Ann and family were listed in ======= style='font-size:14.0pt'> In 1860 Elisha, Mary Ann and family were listed in >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 the Mason County Illinois Census.  After Joseph's death, Mary Ann tried to get survivor's benefits stating that she had been dependent on his income for her support and the support of her three minor children.  It states that Elisha deserted the family prior to Joseph's enlistment.  In 1870 Mary Ann is living in Hamilton County Iowa with son Rupert and Elisha is living in Tazewell County Illinois with daughter and son in law, Sarah and James Wineburner.  On September 17, 1878, Mary Ann tries again for benefits and is now listed as the widow of Elisha Meads.  In the 1880 Tazewell County Illinois Census, Mary Ann is listed as living at the County Poor Farm. On February 11, 1887 a letter was written to the Post Master of Pekin, Tazewell County Illinois trying to find the location of Mary Ann.  The reply states that she had died.  In the letter the Post Master J.S. Allen stated he knew this information because Mary Ann was the aunt of his wife. August 8, 1892 John Meads tried to get benefits as the oldest living sibling of Joseph and he is living in Killbourne, Mason County Illinois.

The Nalley- Moose Connection148

 

Sisters, Sabina and Sarah Moose, married brothers, John and Zachariah Nalley who were sons of Levi Nalley. Levi married Rebecca Bartley in Belmont County, Ohio on 23 Jun 1825148, 150. Levi and Rebecca are buried in the Barber Ridge Cemetery in Wayne Township. Levis marker reads, born in Prince Geo. Co., Maryland on 19 Apr 1776 and dies 10-20-1879. He would have been 103 years old. However ======= w:st="on">Township. Levi s marker reads, born in Prince Geo. Co., Maryland on 19 Apr 1776 and dies 10-20-1879 . He would have been 103 years old. However >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 in the 1850- 1870 census listings, he is never listed as being born in 1776 and is 10 to 15 years younger than he should be if born in 1776.

 

Rebecca Nalley died on 25 Jun 1861 at the age of 62 years, 2 months and 15 days. Rebecca was not the mother of John and Zachariah and their mother remains unknown.

 

2. Sabina Moose148, ( John Sr, ), born about 1820 in Pa married John Nalley born in Ohio on 4 Jul 1810 in Ohio148 and died on 15 Mar 1917 in Monroe County, Ohio12. The Nalley Tree on Monroe County OGS site states that John Nalley died in 1917 which would make him 107 years old. In the 1880 census he is 62 years old and ======= style='mso-spacerun:yes'> In the 1880 census he is 62 years old and >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 married to Sarah age 63. This would make his birth date about 1816. In 1850 he is 35 and Sabina is 30.

 

Sabina died before 1860 and after 1850. John then married Sarah Dearth and later married Hannah Keyser. Sabina and John Nalley had the following children shown in the 1850 census of Wayne, Monroe, Ohio148.

Jacobs birth place is reported as Virginia. His parents and John Jrs parents were recorded as John and Mary Ann Moose12 ======= 1808. Jacob s birth place is reported as Virginia. His parents and John Jr s parents were recorded as John and Mary Ann Moose12 >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 which proves that Jacob and John Jr. are brothers. John Jr. died on 17 May 1879 at the age of 72 years, 11 months and 11 days or a calculated birth date of 6 June 180612. He was born in Green Co., Pa. George W. Moose died 17 Nov 1882 but his parents ar not listed. He died in Wayne Township and it states that he was born in Belmont Co., Ohio but this is probably incorrect. George was 78 years, 8 months and 16 days old with a calculated birth date of 1 March 1804. All died in Wayne Township.

 

Elizabeth Moose Moore died on 12 Apr 1887 in Menard County, Illinois. She was listed as 86 when she died.

 

Joseph Moose was born in Maryland around 1800 and died before the census time in1870.

 

If these are brothers, then it would appear that John and George were born in Pennsylvania and then the family would have had to move to Virginia (probably toward Ohio in area nearer to the Ohio River or present West Virginia) where Jacob was born. They then moved on to Belmont County and eventually to Monroe County. The fact that Joseph was born in Maryland does not fit smoothly with other records but Maryland is of course just south of PA. John Sr. does not appear in the Union Church Records of Lehigh County but brothers born before him and after him are listed6 <<<<<<< HEAD and do appear as sons of John Jacob Mussgenung ======= and do appear as sons of John Jacob Mussgenung >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 II. Then explaining how Joseph was born in Maryland is not that simple since John Senior was most likely born in PA. He would have married and then moved to Maryland for a short period of time before returning to PA. He would then need to move to Virginia for the birth of George and then back to PA for the birth of John Jr. and Jacob and then to Belmont County, Ohio. Perhaps the birth place information is not correct or possibly one or more of these people came from different families.

 

This work still leaves one uncertain about the relationship between George Moose and brothers, John and Jacob Moose. But still no information has been found to prove that George was or was not the son of John Sr. His close proximity with the other members of John <<<<<<< HEAD Srs family certainly leads one to believe that they may be closely related.

======= Sr s family certainly leads one to believe that they may be closely related.

Chapter Three More Information on the Ancestors of John Moose Sr.1,2,3,7,41, 163A-E

 

There are several family trees on ancestry.com which present a scenario covering the Moose Family that moved from Germany setting up in Pennsylvania and then splitting into three factions. One remained in Pennsylvania; one moved to North Carolina and one moved to Ohio. The Ohio Clan moved first to Belmont County and then to Monroe County. There is another group of Moose Families in Monroe County that I was unable to tie to the group that came from PA via Belmont County.

 

Gall David Mussgenug or Mussgnug was born in Solligen Germany about 1596. He married Barbara about 1821 and Johann Nicholas Mussgenug was born in 1640 in about 1596. He married Barbara about 1821 and Johann Nicholas Mussgenug was born in 1640 in >>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 w:st="on">Solligen, Germany. Johann Nicholas I married Anna Elizabeth Repple on 13 Oct 1665 in Germany.

 

Johann Nicholas I and Anna had a son Johann Nicholas I and Anna had a son >>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>Johann Nicholas II born on 1 April 1685. He married Anna Catherine Hess and they had a son Johann Jacob I born on 10 Feb 1718 in Solligen, Germany and died in Allentown, PA. He married Anna Margaret Fuger and they had five daughters and two sons. One son was Johann JacobII born about 1740 in Germany and who died 1823 in Gettysburg, PA. He married Elizabeth Hoffman on 25 Feb 1766. They had seven sons and one daughter. One of these sons was probably John Moose Sr. born 16 September 1778 in Lehigh County, Pennsylvania.

Chapter Six The Ullom Family

 

Introduction

 

Martha Mattie Halls mother, was Rachel Ullom who was born on 4 May 184812,50,81 in Monroe County and was the daughter of Stephen Ullom and Eleanor (Ellen, Nellie, Ella) Mitchell50. Stephen was born in 1813 and was the son of George S. Ullom* and Margaret Bowen. Georges ======= style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-weight:bold'> Mattie Hall s mother, was Rachel Ullom who was born on 4 May 184812,50,81 in Monroe County and was the daughter of Stephen Ullom and Eleanor (Ellen, Nellie, Ella) Mitchell50. Stephen was born in 1813 and was the son of George S. Ullom* and Margaret Bowen. George s >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 parents were Peter Ulm Ullom and Margaretha Smith. The Ullom line is traced to Jacab Ulm and Maria Boeshaar in 1720. Other names are Wenich and Bayshore. The Ulms are of German Heritage52.

 

*Stephen Ullom is listed55 as a member of Company C of the 2nd West Virginia Cavalry. He died in Nov 1862 in Mt. Pleasant, Virginia of Typhoid Fever56. Stephen and Nellie are buried in the Pioneer Cemetery in Woodsfield160.

 

* *George Ullom was born in Virginia, now West Virginia, in 1779. It is possible that he is the George Ullom who helped build the Courthouse in Greene County, PA in 1797. This log building is still in existence and is said to be the Number 1 tourist attraction in Greene County, PA. (Greene County PA. Cornerstone Genealogy Society, www.cornerstonegenealogy.com).

 

George Ulloms wife was Margaret Bowens and ======= text-autospace:none'>George Ullom s wife was Margaret Bowen s and >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 her family is traced to 1585 in Wales via on-line family trees sources52,53. Margaret was born in Greene County, PA in 1779, and she married George Ullom on 8 Aug 1801 in Greene County, PA. The Bowen surname begins as Evan, then Owen and then Bowen. Other surnames in this line are; Gainor, Cadwaladr, Lloyd, Carter, Wilford, Humphrey and Burgess. Margaret Bowens parents are Henry Bowen (1715-1784) and Anna Moon(e) (1722-Abt 1789). Anna Moone Bowens parents were Simon Moone and Laurentha Humphrey. Simons father was James Moon (1669- 4 Jun 1755). He was born in Sommerset, England and died in Bucks County, PA. Simons mother was Mary Wilsford (1671-bef 1714). The Moones can be traced back to 1570 in Lancaster, England. One additional surname is Dilsworth. Most of these people are from Wales52,53.

Ohio, Elizabeth Bottenfield, Rebecca Jane Bottenfield, Margaret Bottenfield, Nancy Ellen Bottenfield of Vinton Co., Ohio, Shadrach Bottenfield of Greene Co., Pa., minor heirs of Samuel Bottenfield, deceased and Isaac Bottenfield, William Bottenfield, Hiram Bottenfield, Mary Ann Dickey and Samuel Dickey her husband of Monroe Co. will take notice that Thomas Mitchell, administrator of the estate of Samuel Bottenfield, deceased filed a petition against them to be authorized to complete a certain contract for the sale of land executed by said decedent in his lifetime to one Peter Stine.

DAVID ULLOM, farmer and >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 stock-grower and dealer in wool, was born in Aleppo Township, this county, December 11, 1845, and is a son of Peter and Matilda (Kinney) Ullom, natives of Pennsylvania.  His father has spent a long life as a farmer, being now eighty years of age.  Mr. David Ullom is the youngest in the family of six children and was reared on the farm with his parents, receiving a common school education.  He has spent his life as a farmer and has given a good deal of attention to the raising of fine stock.  He has engaged in wool buying extensively and has been very successful.  Mr. Ullom owns a fine farm of 200 acres, and is one <<<<<<< HEAD of Aleppos most prominent citizens.  On October 14, 1869, he married Mary Ellen, daughter of Jacob and Catharine (Huffman) King.  Her parents were of English and German origin.  Mr. King is a farmer by occupation.  Mr. and Mrs. Ullom have one childFrankie D.  The family are members of the Church of God.  Mr. Ullom is a trustee in the church and secretary and treasurer of the Sabbath-school.  In politics he is a Democrat. Introduction

 

Stephen Ulloms wife was Ellenor Mitchell. Sometimes she is referred to as Nellie and in fact on her grave marker in the Pioneer Cemetery, she is Nellie Ullom wife of S.Ullom. Also, on her request for Stephens pension she gave the name Ellen. On her daughter Rachels death cert her name is Ella Mitchell. There are around 60 family trees on Ancestry.com that cover the Mitchell Family. These trees dont always agree ======= text-autospace:none'>Stephen Ullom s wife was Ellenor Mitchell. There are around 60 family trees on Ancestry.com that cover the Mitchell Family. These trees don t always agree >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 especially as you go back in time. In order to present a reasonable picture of the Mitchell and related families not all of the various branches will be pursued and any contrary information will be shown. All information that can be verified through census and other records will be presented.

Thomas Mitchell, Martha Halls Great-Grandfather, built the first water wheel mill on Whitten Fork in 1826 in Monroe County. It was a frame building of two stories and 30 feet by 40 feet. He also built the first saw mill in 1824. The following advertisement was found in a newspaper article and published in <<<<<<< HEAD Family Research in Monroe County, Ohio by Catherine Foreaker Fedorchak62.

* Notice Valuable saw mill for sale- Thomas Mitchell wishes to sell his mill and farm which resides in Jackson Township on Whittens fork of the Little Muskingum and on the road leading from Woodsfield to the Ohio River, 10 miles from the former and 5 miles from the latter. Mill has two roll of stones, the mill house is a large 3 frame, stones are laurelhill burs, sawmill is adjoining the mill and is also in completer operation and is calculated to cut from 1,000 to 15,000 feet of plank in one day. Farm consists of 80 acres, mostly all bottom land. Log dwelling house and store room, small barn, a good well of water at the door, also a quantity of good bearing fruit trees. Thomas Mitchell

Bowen/Moone/Wilsford/Boeshaar/Carter/Hymphrey

 

Margaret Bowen is listed as the wife of George Stephen Ullom in over 30 Family Trees on Ancestry.com. Margaret was said to be the daughter of Henry Bowen and Anna Moone and thus tied to a rich hstory covering the family names above and many more and going back to England in the 1500s. However, this Margaret Bowen does not appear to be the daughter of Henry and Anna because the ages are not compatible. She could be a grand-daughter but that has not be proven.So these families cannot be connected through this relatinship

As mentioned earlier, Clifford and Martha had eight children, six girls and two boys. I will cover each family in this Chapter.

 

5. Lela Marie Moose17,18 ( John Sr., George, John J, Clifford), (Thomas Hall, John M.)

 

Lela was the oldest child and was born in Monroe County on17 Aug 189618. On Nov 12, 1915 she married Ernest R. Bates in Monroe County16. Probate Judge E. J. Thompson performed the ceremony. Ernest Bates was born on 5 July 1890 in Wayne Township18 and was the son of Richard Atherton Bates and Rebecca Letetia Dougherty66. Some time after 1917 and before 1920 the family moved to Oklahoma where Ernest drilled oil wells on one of the Indian Reservations45, 67.

 

 

Ernest and Lela returned to Monroe County after 1920 and Ernest became a farmer. They had three children all born in Monroe County.

 

Probably before 1940, Ernest and Lela moved to Ashland County, Ohio and purchased a farm near Polk on County Rd.601. They later purchased a second farm in Orange Township which was bordered on the north by Township Rd. 700 and on the west by State Rd. 58 and farmed them both for several years45.

 

Ernest and Lela retired on their second farm along Ohio Route 58. Lela died on 22 Dec 1987 at the age of 91 years 4 months and 5 days. Ernest Bates died on 21 Aug 1989 at the age of 99 years 1 month and 16 days37,45, 70.
